      <div xml:id="preface" type="section" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
        <head>Preface</head>
        <!-- C.4 d.init. -->
        <!-- C.4 q.2-3 d.p.c.3 -->
        <p part="N">
        Perhaps the most interesting text in the case is Gratian's
        one and only <hi rend="italic">dictum</hi>, C.4 q.2-3
        d.p.c.3. "Set obicitur illud beati Bricii, qui uoce pueri
        xxx dies ab ortu habentis innocens probatus est. Set miracula
        diuina sunt admiranda, non in exemplum humane actionis
        trahenda." The Latin of the first sentence is somewhat
        opaque. Taking the accusative plural <hi rend="italic">dies</hi>
        as the object of <hi rend="italic">habentis</hi>, and
        supplying <hi rend="italic">exemplum</hi> because it is
        neuter and can be construed with <hi rend="italic">illud</hi>,
        the sentence can be literally translated as "But that
        [example] of blessed Brice is objected, who was proved
        innocent by the voice of the child having thirty days from
        its birth or origin." The <hi rend="italic">dictum</hi> can
        be translated into more idiomatic English as "But a
        counter-example is that of St. Brice, who was proved innocent
        by the word of a thirty-day-old child. But divine miracles
        are to be wondered at, not to be taken as a pattern for
        human action."
        </p>
        <p part="N">
        Gratian is referring to a story from Gregory of Tours,
        <title level="m">History of the Franks</title>, II.1, about
        St. Brice (†.444), St. Martin's controversial immediate
        successor as bishop of Tours. This is the only mention of
        Brice in the <title level="m">Decretum</title>, and
        <title level="m">History of the Franks</title> falls outside
        what we normally consider to be the boundaries of Gratian's
        formal or material sources. (Friedberg attributes the story
        to the <title level="m">Life of St. Martin</title> by
        Sulpicius Severus, although he really seems to have had in
        mind an unrelated story from the third book of Sulpicius's
        <title level="m">Dialogues</title> in which Marin compares
        Brice to Judas. In any event Friedberg was wrong, the proper
        attribution is to Gregory.) Gregory relates the story of a
        nun or consecrated virgin serving as a laundress for Brice's
        episcopal household who became pregnant and delivered a
        child. The people of Tours, with whom Brice was already
        quite unpopular, suspected that he was the father. Brice
        had the thirty-day-old infant brought to him, and questioned
        the child publicly concerning his paternity. Through the
        saint's miraculous intervention, the child spoke plainly,
        answering that Brice was not its father.
        </p>
        <p part="N">
        The <hi rend="italic">dictum</hi> is relevant in its immediate
        context, since Gratian is concluding his treatment of the
        second question, whether someone under the age of fourteen
        is able to testify in a criminal case. But Gratian's reference
        to this obscure story also seems intended to caution against
        depending on miracles as a regular part of criminal procedure,
        and by extension implies a negative judgement on the validity
        of trial by ordeal.
        </p>
        <p part="N">
        <note place="foot" anchored="true">"It is remarkable that in his dicta
        Gratian refers to sources that are not cited in the Decretum.
        Many biblical citations, for example, are found only in the
        dicta. They are often tied to important theological reflections
        ..." (Landau, "Gratian and the Decretum Gratiani", 41.)</note>
        </p>
        <!-- 4.4.1 -->
        <!-- 4.6.1 and 4.6.2 rubrics -->
        <p part="N">The text of the rubrics for 4.6.1 and 4.6.2 is quite similar in all
        four R1 mss., and substantially different from the readings reported in
        Fr. 4.6.1: "Qui in accusatione episcopi culpabilis inuenitur ad
        arguendum de cetero non admittatur nisi propriam causam ciuilem
        solummodo asserere uoluerit" in Aa Bc Fd P, and "In ciuili et proprio
        dumtaxat negotio ad arguendum admittitur, qui in episcopi accusatione
        culpabilis inuenitur" in Fr. 4.6.2: "Non negatur audientia in propria
        causa cuius accusatio interdicitur" in Aa Bc Fd P, and "Propriam causam
        agere ualet cui accusare non licet" in Fr.</p>
        <!--
          "(Admont) Aa contains the same text (as Bc Fd P) with interpolations
          from the second recension in the main section of its two volumes."
          Winroth, The Making of Gratian's Decretum, 122.
        -->
        <p part="N">There are two marginal glosses in the Aa text of C.4 that refer to
        Burchard's <title level="m">Decretum</title>: "B.xvi. Nemo ſimul ſit."
        (Burchard 16.15) at 4.4.1, and "B.i. Qͥſqͥs." (Burchard 1.160) at 4.6.1.
        A rubric in between C.4 and C.5 ("Explicit liber quintus, incipit liber
        sextus, de episcoporum accusationibus") indicates a non-standard
        division of Aa into books.</p>
        <!-- Barcelona (Bc) -->
        <p part="N">The order of rubrics in C.4 q.4 is reversed in Bc. The rubric for
        4.4.2 ("Quilibet in causa duas personas gerere non valet") appears
        before 4.4.1, and the rubric for 4.4.1 ("Accusator, testis vel iudex
        aliquis simul esse non potest") appears before 4.4.2. Bc includes two
        canons — 4.6.3 and 4.6.4 — not listed in Winroth's appendix and not
        found in either Aa or P.</p>
        <!-- Paris (P) -->
        <p part="N">The quality of scribal workmanship in P is visibly less professional
        than that in either Aa or Bc.</p>
        <!--
        cf. Mantello and Rigg
        A.G. Rigg, CB "Orthography and Punctuation", 79
        "Before a vowel, -<hi rend="italic">ti</hi>- is usually spelled -<hi rend="italic">ci</hi>-,
        e.g., <hi rend="italic">racio</hi> = <hi rend="italic">ratio</hi>,
        except after <hi rend="italic">s</hi> and <hi rend="italic">x</hi>,
        e.g. <hi rend="italic">mixtio</hi>."
        -->
        <p part="N">
        In addition to scribal errors, Aa, Bc, and P reflect divergence from
        Classical Latin orthography for
        <hi rend="italic">ci</hi> and <hi rend="italic">ti</hi>.
        Aa: <hi rend="italic">spacium</hi>;
        Bc: <hi rend="italic">defitiens</hi>,
        <hi rend="italic">iuditio</hi> and
        <hi rend="italic">iuditium</hi>, and
        <hi rend="italic">prouintie</hi>; and
        P: <hi rend="italic">accionis</hi>,
        <hi rend="italic">audiencia</hi>, and
        <hi rend="italic">tercio</hi>.
        </p>
      </div>
